5000|$|From 1872, distant <b>signal</b> <b>arms</b> (see below) were {{distinguished}} {{by having a}} [...] "fishtail" [...] notch cut into the end. All <b>signal</b> <b>arms</b> were still painted red at this time. In the 1920s, the British railway companies began to colour their distant <b>signal</b> <b>arms</b> yellow to better distinguish them from the red stop signals. The red lenses in distant signals were changed to yellow at the same time. The practice of using red distant arms has survived in some countries however.|$|R
